1	   Title: Predicting motivation: computational models of PFC can explain neural coding of 2	   motivation and effort-based decision-making in health and disease 3	   4	   Abbreviated title: Computational models of PFC and effort-based behavior 5	   6	   Authors: Eliana Vassena12, James Deraeve2, William H. Alexander2 7	1   . Donders Institute for Brain, Cognition and Behavior, Radboud University Nijmegen 8	2   . Department of experimental psychology, Ghent University 9	   10	   11	   12	   Corresponding author: Eliana Vassena, Donders Institute for Brain Cognition and Behavior, 13	   Radboud University Nijmegen, Kapittelweg 29, 6525 EN, Nijmegen, The Netherlands. +31 14	   (0)24 3610618 15	   email: e.vassena@donders.ru.nl 16	   17	   18	   19	   20	   21	   22	  

	  

1	  

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/171637; this version posted August 2, 2017. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder, who has granted bioRxiv a license to display the preprint in perpetuity. It is made available under aCC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.

23	   Abstract
24	   Human behavior is strongly driven by the pursuit of rewards. In daily life, however, benefits 25	   mostly come at a cost, often requiring that effort be exerted in order to obtain potential benefits. 26	   Medial prefrontal cortex (MPFC) and dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) are frequently 27	   implicated in the expectation of effortful control, showing increased activity as a function of 28	   predicted task difficulty. Such activity partially overlaps with expectation of reward, and has 29	   been observed both during decision-making and during task preparation. Recently, novel 30	   computational frameworks have been developed to explain activity in these regions during 31	   cognitive control, based on the principle of prediction and prediction error (PRO model, 32	   Alexander and Brown, 2011, HER Model, Alexander and Brown, 2015). Despite the broad 33	   explanatory power of these models, it is not clear whether they can also accommodate effects 34	   related to the expectation of effort observed in MPFC and DLPFC. Here, we propose a 35	   translation of these computational frameworks to the domain of effort-based behavior. First, we 36	   discuss how the PRO model, based on prediction error, can explain effort-related activity in 37	   MPFC, by reframing effort-based behavior in a predictive context. We propose that MPFC 38	   activity reflects monitoring of motivationally relevant variables (such as effort and reward), by 39	   coding expectations, and discrepancies from such expectations. Moreover, we derive 40	   behavioral and neural model-based predictions for healthy controls and clinical populations 41	   with impairments of motivation. Second, we illustrate the possible translation to effort-based 42	   behavior of the HER model, an extended version of PRO model based on hierarchical error 43	   prediction, developed to explain MPFC-DLPFC interactions. We derive behavioral predictions 44	   which describe how effort and reward information is coded in PFC, and how changing the 45	   configuration of such environmental information might affect decision-making and task46	   performance involving motivation. 47	  

	  

2	  

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/171637; this version posted August 2, 2017. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder, who has granted bioRxiv a license to display the preprint in perpetuity. It is made available under aCC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.

48	   Introduction
49	   Attaining a goal often requires commitment, implementation of a precise course of actions, and 50	   deployment of sufficient resources to reach successful completion. How humans fulfill this 51	   process is largely investigated in the field of cognitive neuroscience under the term of goal52	   directed behavior. A crucial underlying cognitive mechanism is prediction: the ability to 53	   evaluate the environment, formulate expectations about future events based on previous 54	   experiences, and finally compare such expectations with subsequent outcomes in order to 55	   update one’s knowledge about the current state of the world. Furthermore, adaptive interaction 56	   with the environment entails predicting the impact of one’s action and evaluating outcomes. 57	   The human Prefrontal Cortex (PFC) is the neural machinery that supports crucial mechanisms 58	   involved in goal-directed behavior (Miller & Cohen, 2001). In particular, the medial portion of 59	   PFC (MPFC, including dorsal Anterior Cingulate Cortex, dACC) is implicated in prediction 60	   and outcome evaluation (Alexander & Brown, 2011; Jahn, Nee, Alexander, & Brown, 2014), 61	   including situations in which the outcome carries value for the agent, such as a reward 62	   (Rushworth, Walton, Kennerley, & Bannerman, 2004; Silvetti, Seurinck, & Verguts, 2011, 63	   2013; Vassena, Krebs, Silvetti, Fias, & Verguts, 2014). Notably, a variety of other functions 64	   have been attributed to MPFC (Vassena, Holroyd, & Alexander, 2017), including error 65	   monitoring, (Holroyd, Nieuwenhuis, Mars, & Coles, 2004; van Veen, Holroyd, Cohen, Stenger, 66	   & Carter, 2004), conflict detection (Botvinick, Braver, Barch, Carter, & Cohen, 2001), pain and 67	   affect processing (Bush, Luu, & Posner, 2000; Nee, Kastner, & Brown, 2011), and value-based 68	   decision-making (Rangel & Hare, 2010; Rushworth, Kolling, Sallet, & Mars, 2012; Rushworth 69	   & Behrens, 2008). Recent computational work has explained this array of empirical findings 70	   under the unifying principle of prediction and prediction error. In this framework, MPFC 71	   formulates predictions tracking stimuli, actions and outcomes, and computes a signal termed 72	   prediction error, which scales with the discrepancy between predicted and actual outcomes

	  

3	  

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/171637; this version posted August 2, 2017. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder, who has granted bioRxiv a license to display the preprint in perpetuity. It is made available under aCC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
73	   (Predicted Response Outcome model, PRO model, Alexander & Brown, 2011). This 74	   mechanism allows rapid prediction updating according to environmental feedback, be it an 75	   error, a painful stimulus, or a reward. An extended version of the same model, the Hierarchical 76	   Error Representation model (HER, Alexander & Brown 2015), expands the same 77	   computational principle in a hierarchical architecture, capturing more complex high-level 78	   cognitive processes involving the interaction of MPFC and dorsolateral PFC (DLPFC), 79	   typically associated with higher-level cognitive functions such as working memory and goal80	   maintenance (Miller & Cohen, 2001).
81	   The goal of this manuscript is to explore the power of these computational accounts, in terms of 82	   generating novel neural and behavioral predictions for untested contexts and populations. These 83	   frameworks have proven useful across several fields of cognition, yet they have not been put to 84	   test in the field of effortful behavior and motivation. Goal-directed behavior generally involves 85	   competing factors, including the value of the prospective goals, how much effort one is willing 86	   to exert to attain the desired goal, and preparation for the necessary effortful performance 87	   (Botvinick & Braver, 2015; Westbrook & Braver, 2013, 2015). First, we will describe MPFC 88	   involvement in effort-based behavior. Then, we illustrate how the PRO model can be 89	   generalized to the domain of motivation. We propose that MPFC activity reflects monitoring of 90	   motivationally relevant variables such as reward and required effort, instead of coding an 91	   explicit cost-benefit or choice signal per se. We illustrate novel model-based simulations, as 92	   well as theoretical predictions, which can be used to guide further empirical enquiry. We 93	   discuss how the PRO framework makes neural and behavioral predictions for clinical 94	   conditions in which motivation is impaired, such as depression and other psychiatric disorders 95	   (Treadway, Bossaller, Shelton, & Zald, 2012). Subsequently, we discuss the future directions in 96	   translating the HER model to the domain of motivation, extrapolating behavioral predictions.

	  

4	  

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/171637; this version posted August 2, 2017. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder, who has granted bioRxiv a license to display the preprint in perpetuity. It is made available under aCC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.

97	   From such predictions, we derive implications for measuring and potentially training 98	   motivation-related cognitive mechanisms in clinical populations.
99	   Effort-based decision-making and performance in MPFC
100	   Experimental manipulation of effort in behavioral and neuroimaging experiments has yielded a 101	   wealth of findings in the past decade. Typically, effort is perceived as aversive (Kool, 102	   McGuire, Rosen, & Botvinick, 2010), yet humans decide to engage in it when doing so leads to 103	   a benefit, such as a reward. In the framework of decision-making and neuroeconomics, the net 104	   value of a potential reward is discounted (i.e. decreased) by the amount of effort required to 105	   obtain the reward (Apps, Grima, Manohar, & Husain, 2015; Hartmann, Hager, Tobler, & 106	   Kaiser, 2013; Nishiyama, 2014). This seems to hold across different types of effort (Nishiyama, 107	   2016), and guides decisions to engage one’s resources in the task at hand (Kurzban, 108	   Duckworth, Kable, & Myers, 2013). Several studies in animals described the neural 109	   mechanisms underlying this cost-benefit evaluation, showing a pivotal role of MPFC in 110	   interaction with striatal and sub-cortical nuclei (Hosokawa, Kennerley, Sloan, & Wallis, 2013; 111	   Kennerley, Dahmubed, Lara, & Wallis, 2009; Rushworth & Behrens, 2008; Walton, Kennerley, 112	   Bannerman, Phillips, & Rushworth, 2006; Walton et al., 2009; Walton, Bannerman, Alterescu, 113	   & Rushworth, 2003;. Walton, Bannerman, & Rushworth, 2002; Walton, Rudebeck, 114	   Bannerman, & Rushworth, 2007). In the last few years a similar network has been 115	   characterized in humans. Lesions of MPFC may result in a condition known as akinetic mutism 116	   (Devinsky, Morrell, & Vogt, 1995), whereby patients show difficulties in initiating speech and 117	   movement, not due to an impairment of related systems, but rather to the inability or “lack of 118	   will” to start it. Electrical stimulation of the same region seems to induce a general feeling of 119	   being more motivated and more willing to persevere in effortful endeavors (Parvizi, 120	   Rangarajan, Shirer, Desai, & Greicius, 2013, although this single-case study presents some 121	   methodological caveats). More recently, neuroimaging studies have shown involvement of the

	  

5	  

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/171637; this version posted August 2, 2017. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder, who has granted bioRxiv a license to display the preprint in perpetuity. It is made available under aCC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
122	   striatum and MPFC in effort-reward trade-off computations (Botvinick, Huffstetler, & 123	   McGuire, 2009; Croxson, Walton, O’Reilly, Behrens, & Rushworth, 2009; Engstrom, 124	   Landtblom, & Karlsson, 2013; Massar, Libedinsky, Weiyan, Huettel, & Chee, 2015; Mulert et 125	   al., 2008). Furthermore, expecting to perform a more cognitively challenging task is associated 126	   with increased activity in striatum and MPFC, overlapping with activity induced by the 127	   prospect of a higher reward (Krebs, Boehler, Roberts, Song, & Woldorff, 2012; Vassena, 128	   Silvetti, et al., 2014).
129	   These results suggest a crucial contribution of MPFC to effort-based behavior, hypothesized to 130	   compute the willingness to engage in the task at hand, given that upon completion a reward will 131	   be received. This principle has been defined in recent theories (Holroyd & Yeung, 2012; 132	   Shenhav, Botvinick, & Cohen, 2013), and formalized in a computational model wherein MPFC 133	   calculates the value of boosting certain actions over others, accordingly guiding behavior in 134	   cognitive and physical tasks (Verguts, Vassena, & Silvetti, 2015). Such computations are 135	   thought to influence decision-making (Treadway, Buckholtz, et al., 2012), resource allocation, 136	   task preparation (Kurniawan, Guitart-Masip, Dayan, & Dolan, 2013; Vassena, Silvetti, et al., 137	   2014), and response vigor (Kurniawan, Guitart-Masip, & Dolan, 2011), even at the lowest 138	   layers of the motor system (Vassena, Cobbaert, Andres, Fias, & Verguts, 2015).
139	   In summary, growing evidence supports a pivotal role of MPFC in effort-based behavior. 140	   However, such empirical effects and theorizing efforts have so far failed to provide a precise 141	   computational characterization able to account for this line of evidence within other existing 142	   computational frameworks of MPFC function.
143	   The Predicted Response Outcome (PRO) Model
144	   According to the PRO model, MPFC implements two core mechanisms: 1) learning to predict 145	   the outcome of responses generated in response to environmental stimuli and 2) signaling

	  

6	  

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/171637; this version posted August 2, 2017. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder, who has granted bioRxiv a license to display the preprint in perpetuity. It is made available under aCC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.

146	   discrepancies between predictions and observations. Using these two primary signals as an 147	   index of MPFC activity, the PRO model has previously been shown to account for a range of 148	   effects observed in MPFC related to cognitive control and decision making, including effects of 149	   error, conflict, and error likelihood. Critically, the PRO model explains these effects without 150	   reference to the underlying affective import: feedback related to behavioral error is equivalent 151	   to feedback indicating correct behavior in the sense that both forms of feedback constitute an 152	   outcome that can be predicted on the basis of task-related stimuli. An open question, therefore, 153	   is how the PRO model might be extended to account for effects in which behavior is influenced 154	   not only by the likelihood of an event occurring, but also by the value of that event.

