883	   Figures and figures captions 884	  
885	   886	   Figure 1. PRO model architecture (adapted from Alexander and Brown, 2011). The circles 887	   outside the box represent environmental input (stimulus and feedback). The circles inside the 888	   box represent units coding neural activity. Stimulus representations code environmental stimuli. 889	   Depending on previous occurrence, certain stimuli predict certain outcomes, as coded in 890	   outcome prediction units. Outcome units code real environmental outcome (feedback). A 891	   comparison between outcome prediction units and outcome units results in an error signal 892	   (discrepancy between predicted and actual outcome). This error signal feeds back into the 893	   outcome prediction unit, to update such predictions. 894	   895	   896	   897	   898	  

	  

37	  

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/171637; this version posted August 2, 2017. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder, who has granted bioRxiv a license to display the preprint in perpetuity. It is made available under aCC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
899	   900	   Figure 2. Model predictions. a. Behavioral predictions. The y-axis shows the probability of 901	   choosing to engage in a task. The x-axis shows four different effort levels (varying 902	   parametrically from easy (level 1) to hard (level 4). The grey line indicates a low reward upon 903	   successful completion. The black line indicates a high reward upon successful completion. The 904	   plot shows that with a low reward, increasing task difficulty reduces the probability of 905	   engaging in the task, while with a high reward the model engages in the increasingly effortful 906	   task anyway. b. Neural predictions. The y-axis shows MPFC activity at the time of cue. The x907	   axis shows the four effort levels. The grey line indicates low reward. The black line indicates 908	   high reward. The plot shows that model activity is overall higher when reward is high. 909	   Moreover, when reward is high activity linearly increases as a function of increasing effort. 910	   When reward is low, model activity only increases up to effort level 3. 911	  

	  

